[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Different fields of study define autocorrelation differently, and not all of these definitions are equivalent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In some fields, the term is used interchangeably with autocovariance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Various time series models incorporate autocorrelation, such as unit root processes, trend-stationary processes, autoregressive processes, and moving average processes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In statistics, the autocorrelation of a real or complex random process is the Pearson correlation between values of the process at different times, as a function of the two times or of the time lag.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Let $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ be a random process over time and $X_{t}$ be the random variable at time t .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator and the bar represents complex conjugation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Note that the expectation may not be well defined.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Suppose that the process has mean $\mu _{t}$ and variance $\sigma _{t}^{2}$ at time t , for each t .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Note that this expression is not well defined for all-time series or processes, because the mean may not exist, or the variance may be zero (for a constant process) or infinite (for processes with distribution lacking well-behaved moments, such as certain types of power law).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] This further implies that the autocovariance and autocorrelation can be expressed as a function of the time-lag, and that this would be an even function of the lag $\tau =t_{2}-t_{1}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] It is common practice in some disciplines (e.g. statistics and time series analysis) to normalize the autocovariance function to get a time-dependent Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] However, in other disciplines (e.g. engineering) the normalization is usually dropped and the terms "autocorrelation" and "autocovariance" are used interchangeably.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] If the function $\rho _{XX}$ is well defined, its value must lie in the range $[-1,1]$ , with 1 indicating perfect correlation and −1 indicating perfect anti-correlation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The normalization is important both because the interpretation of the autocorrelation as a correlation provides a scale-free measure of the strength of statistical dependence, and because the normalization has an effect on the statistical properties of the estimated autocorrelations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] For a WSS process: $\left|\operatorname {R} _{XX}(\tau )\right|\leq \operatorname {R} _{XX}(0)$ Notice that $\operatorname {R} _{XX}(0)$ is always real.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The autocorrelation of a continuous-time white noise signal will have a strong peak (represented by a Dirac delta function) at $\tau =0$ and will be exactly 0 for all other $\tau$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The autocorrelation matrix is used in various digital signal processing algorithms.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] where ${}^{\rm {T}}$ denotes transposition of the vector.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Here ${}^{\rm {H}}$ denotes Hermitian transpose.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In signal processing, the above definition is often used without the normalization, that is, without subtracting the mean and dividing by the variance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] When the autocorrelation function is normalized by mean and variance, it is sometimes referred to as the **autocorrelation coefficient** or autocovariance function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Given a signal $f(t)$ , the continuous autocorrelation $R_{ff}(\tau )$ is most often defined as the continuous cross-correlation integral of $f(t)$ with itself, at lag $\tau$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] where ${\overline {f(t)}}$ represents the complex conjugate of $f(t)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Note that the parameter t in the integral is a dummy variable and is only necessary to calculate the integral.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The above definitions work for signals that are square integrable, or square summable, that is, of finite energy.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Signals that "last forever" are treated instead as random processes, in which case different definitions are needed, based on expected values.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] For processes that are not stationary, these will also be functions of t , or n .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] For processes that are also ergodic, the expectation can be replaced by the limit of a time average.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] These definitions have the advantage that they give sensible well-defined single-parameter results for periodic functions, even when those functions are not the output of stationary ergodic processes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Alternatively, signals that *last forever* can be treated by a short-time autocorrelation function analysis, using finite time integrals.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In the following, we will describe properties of one-dimensional autocorrelations only, since most properties are easily transferred from the one-dimensional case to the multi-dimensional cases.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] These properties hold for wide-sense stationary processes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Multi-dimensional autocorrelation is defined similarly.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] When mean values are subtracted from signals before computing an autocorrelation function, the resulting function is usually called an auto-covariance function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] For data expressed as a discrete sequence, it is frequently necessary to compute the autocorrelation with high computational efficiency.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] A brute force method based on the signal processing definition ${\textstyle R_{xx}(j)=\sum _{n}x_{n}\,{\overline {x}}_{n-j}}$ can be used when the signal size is small.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In this calculation we do not perform the carry-over operation during addition as is usual in normal multiplication.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Note that we can halve the number of operations required by exploiting the inherent symmetry of the autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] While the brute force algorithm is order *n*2, several efficient algorithms exist which can compute the autocorrelation in order *n* log(*n*).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] where IFFT denotes the inverse fast Fourier transform.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Alternatively, a multiple τ correlation can be performed by using brute force calculation for low τ values, and then progressively binning the *X*(*t*) data with a logarithmic density to compute higher values, resulting in the same *n* log(*n*) efficiency, but with lower memory requirements.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] When the true mean $\mu$ and variance $\sigma ^{2}$ are known, this estimate is **unbiased**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The advantage of estimates of the last type is that the set of estimated autocorrelations, as a function of k , then form a function which is a valid autocorrelation in the sense that it is possible to define a theoretical process having exactly that autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Other estimates can suffer from the problem that, if they are used to calculate the variance of a linear combination of the X 's, the variance calculated may turn out to be negative.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In time series analysis, the **Hassani −1/2 theorem** is a finite-sample identity concerning the conventional estimator of the *sample autocorrelation function* (ACF).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The identity follows from the fact that the sample autocovariances are computed after subtracting the sample mean.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Consequently, the centered observations sum to zero, which imposes an algebraic constraint on the full set of sample autocorrelations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The theorem is therefore a property of the estimator and the finite sample, rather than a property of the underlying stochastic process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The result implies that sample autocorrelations across lags are not independent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] It also shows that the sample ACF cannot be positive overall when summed across all positive lags.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] This has led to cautions against interpreting the sum of estimated autocorrelations as a direct measure of total dependence, persistence or long-memory behaviour, since the full-lag sum is fixed at $-1/2$ regardless of the underlying stationary time series.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The theorem has been discussed in relation to diagnostic checking and model selection in time series analysis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In particular, later work has examined its implications for tests based on sample autocorrelations, including the Ljung–Box statistic, and for the interpretation of empirical ACF patterns in short-memory and long-memory processes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The identity has also been used to emphasize the distinction between theoretical autocorrelations of a process and empirical autocorrelations estimated from a finite sample.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The theorem applies to the standard sample-mean-corrected ACF estimator.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] It should not be confused with statements about the sum of the theoretical autocorrelation function of the underlying process, which may vary depending on the model and its parameters.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] With multiple interrelated data series, vector autoregression (VAR) or its extensions are used.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In ordinary least squares (OLS), the adequacy of a model specification can be checked in part by establishing whether there is autocorrelation of the regression residuals.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Problematic autocorrelation of the errors, which themselves are unobserved, can generally be detected because it produces autocorrelation in the observable residuals.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] While it does not bias the OLS coefficient estimates, the standard errors tend to be underestimated (and the t-scores overestimated) when the autocorrelations of the errors at low lags are positive.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The traditional test for the presence of first-order autocorrelation is the Durbin–Watson statistic or, if the explanatory variables include a lagged dependent variable, Durbin's h statistic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The Durbin-Watson can be linearly mapped however to the Pearson correlation between values and their lags.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] A more flexible test, covering autocorrelation of higher orders and applicable whether or not the regressors include lags of the dependent variable, is the Breusch–Godfrey test.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] This involves an auxiliary regression, wherein the residuals obtained from estimating the model of interest are regressed on (a) the original regressors and (b) *k* lags of the residuals, where 'k' is the order of the test.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] The simplest version of the test statistic from this auxiliary regression is *TR*2, where *T* is the sample size and *R*2 is the coefficient of determination.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Under the null hypothesis of no autocorrelation, this statistic is asymptotically distributed as $\chi ^{2}$ with *k* degrees of freedom.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] Responses to nonzero autocorrelation include generalized least squares and the Newey–West HAC estimator (Heteroskedasticity and Autocorrelation Consistent).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] In the estimation of a moving average model (MA), the autocorrelation function is used to determine the appropriate number of lagged error terms to be included.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] This is based on the fact that for an MA process of order *q*, we have $R(\tau )\neq 0$ , for $\tau =0,1,\ldots ,q$ , and $R(\tau )=0$ , for $\tau >q$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] A time series of a random variable has serial dependence if the value at some time t in the series is statistically dependent on the value at another time s .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] A series is serially independent if there is no dependence between any pair.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/autocorrelation] If a time series $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is stationary, then statistical dependence between the pair $(X_{t},X_{s})$ would imply that there is statistical dependence between all pairs of values at the same lag $\tau =s-t$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] The intention is to detect those particular components that would fail as a result of the initial, high-failure rate portion of the bathtub curve of component reliability.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] If the burn-in period is made sufficiently long (and, perhaps, artificially stressful), the system can then be trusted to be mostly free of further early failures once the burn-in process is complete.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] Theoretically, any weak components would fail during the "Burn In" time allowing those parts to be replaced.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] Replacing the weak components would prevent premature failure, infant mortality failure, or other latent defects.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] When the equivalent lifetime of the stress is extended into the increasing part of the bathtub-like failure-rate curve, the effect of the burn-in is a reduction of product lifetime.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] In a mature production it is not easy to determine whether there is a decreasing failure rate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] To determine the failure time distribution for a very low percentage of the production, one would have to destroy a very large number of devices.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] By stressing all devices for a certain burn-in time the devices with the highest failure rate fail first and can be taken out of the cohort.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] Thus by applying a burn-in, early in-use system failures can be avoided at the expense (tradeoff) of a reduced yield caused by the burn-in process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] When possible, it is better to eliminate the root cause of early failures than doing a burn-in.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] Because of this, a process that initially uses burn-in may eventually phase it out as the various root causes for failures are identified and eliminated.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] For electronic components, burn-in is frequently conducted at elevated temperature and perhaps elevated voltage.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] This process may also be called **heat soaking**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] The components may be under continuous test or simply tested at the end of the burn-in period.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] There is another use of the term by some audiophiles, who leave new audio equipment turned on for multiple days or weeks, to get the components to achieve optimal performance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/burn-in] However, many debates have arisen about the benefits of this practice.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In thermodynamics, the principle of **detailed balance** says that every process of energy transfer in one direction must also allow energy transfer in the opposite direction, and in equilibrium, the flux in both directions must be equal.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For example, the principle can be used in kinetic systems which are decomposed into elementary processes (collisions, or steps, or elementary reactions).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] It states that at equilibrium, each elementary process is in equilibrium with its reverse process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance was explicitly introduced for collisions by Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In 1872, he proved his H-theorem using this principle.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The arguments in favor of this property are founded upon microscopic reversibility.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Five years before Boltzmann, James Clerk Maxwell used the principle of detailed balance for gas kinetics with the reference to the principle of sufficient reason.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] He compared the idea of detailed balance with other types of balancing (like cyclic balance) and found that "Now it is impossible to assign a reason" why detailed balance should be rejected (p.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In 1901, Rudolf Wegscheider introduced the principle of detailed balance for chemical kinetics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In particular, he demonstrated that the irreversible cycles ${\ce {A1->A2->\cdots ->A_{\mathit {n}}->A1}}$ are impossible and found explicitly the relations between kinetic constants that follow from the principle of detailed balance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In 1931, Lars Onsager used these relations in his works, for which he was awarded the 1968 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance has been used in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods since their invention in 1953.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In particular, in the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and in its important particular case, Gibbs sampling, it is used as a simple and reliable condition to provide the desirable equilibrium state.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Now, the principle of detailed balance is a standard part of the university courses in statistical mechanics, physical chemistry, chemical and physical kinetics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The microscopic "reversing of time" turns at the kinetic level into the "reversing of arrows": the elementary processes transform into their reverse processes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The equilibrium ensemble should be invariant with respect to this transformation because of microreversibility and the uniqueness of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] This leads us immediately to the concept of detailed balance: each process is equilibrated by its reverse process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The macroscopic elementary processes are microscopically distinguishable.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] That is, they represent disjoint sets of microscopic events.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Any of these assumptions may be violated.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For example, Boltzmann's collision can be represented as ${\ce {A_{\mathit {v}}+A_{\mathit {w}}->A_{\mathit {v'}}+A_{\mathit {w'}}}}$ , where ${\ce {A}}_{v}$ is a particle with velocity *v*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Therefore, the collision is transformed into the reverse collision by the *PT* transformation, where *P* is the space inversion and *T* is the time reversal.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Detailed balance for Boltzmann's equation requires *PT*-invariance of collisions' dynamics, not just *T*-invariance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For this purpose, we need to apply additionally the space reversal *P*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Therefore, for the detailed balance in Boltzmann's equation not *T*-invariance but *PT*-invariance is needed.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Equilibrium may be not *T*- or *PT*-invariant even if the laws of motion are invariant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] This non-invariance may be caused by the spontaneous symmetry breaking.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] There exist *nonreciprocal media* (for example, some bi-isotropic materials) without *T* and *PT* invariance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] If different macroscopic processes are sampled from the same elementary microscopic events then macroscopic detailed balance may be violated even when microscopic detailed balance holds.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Now, after almost 150 years of development, the scope of validity and the violations of detailed balance in kinetics seem to be clear.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] *P**ij* = *P*(*X**t* = *j* | *X**t* − 1 = *i*), and π*i* and π*j* are the equilibrium probabilities of being in states *i* and *j*, respectively.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] When Pr(*X**t*−1 = *i*) = π*i* for all *i*, this is equivalent to the joint probability matrix, Pr(*X**t*−1 = *i*, *X**t* = *j*) being symmetric in *i* and *j*; or symmetric in *t* − 1 and *t*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Transition matrices that are symmetric (*P**ij* = *P**ji* or *P*(*s*′, *s*) = *P*(*s*, *s*′)) always have detailed balance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In these cases, a uniform distribution over the states is an equilibrium distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Reversibility is equivalent to Kolmogorov's criterion: the product of transition rates over any closed loop of states is the same in both directions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For example, it implies that, for all *a*, *b* and *c*, $P(a,b)P(b,c)P(c,a)=P(a,c)P(c,b)P(b,a)\,.$ For example, if we have a Markov chain with three states such that only these transitions are possible: $A\to B,B\to C,C\to A,B\to A$ , then they violate Kolmogorov's criterion.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For continuous systems with detailed balance, it may be possible to continuously transform the coordinates until the equilibrium distribution is uniform, with a transition kernel which then is symmetric.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In the case of discrete states, it may be possible to achieve something similar by breaking the Markov states into appropriately-sized degenerate sub-states.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For a Markov transition matrix and a stationary distribution, the detailed balance equations may not be valid.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] However, it can be shown that a unique Markov transition matrix exists which is closest according to the stationary distribution and a given norm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The closest Matrix can be computed by solving a quadratic-convex optimization problem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For many systems of physical and chemical kinetics, detailed balance provides *sufficient conditions* for the strict increase of entropy in isolated systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For example, the famous Boltzmann H-theorem states that, according to the Boltzmann equation, the principle of detailed balance implies positivity of entropy production.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The Boltzmann formula (1872) for entropy production in rarefied gas kinetics with detailed balance served as a prototype of many similar formulas for dissipation in mass action kinetics and generalized mass action kinetics with detailed balance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Nevertheless, the principle of detailed balance is not necessary for entropy growth.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For example, in the linear irreversible cycle ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 -> A1}}$ , entropy production is positive but the principle of detailed balance does not hold.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Thus, the principle of detailed balance is a sufficient but not necessary condition for entropy increase in Boltzmann kinetics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] These relations between the principle of detailed balance and the second law of thermodynamics were clarified in 1887 when Hendrik Lorentz objected to the Boltzmann H-theorem for polyatomic gases.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Lorentz stated that the principle of detailed balance is not applicable to collisions of polyatomic molecules.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Boltzmann immediately invented a new, more general condition sufficient for entropy growth.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Boltzmann's condition holds for all Markov processes, irrespective of time-reversibility.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Later, entropy increase was proved for all Markov processes by a direct method.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] These theorems may be considered as simplifications of the Boltzmann result.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Later, this condition was referred to as the "cyclic balance" condition (because it holds for irreversible cycles) or the "semi-detailed balance" or the "complex balance".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In 1981, Carlo Cercignani and Maria Lampis proved that the Lorentz arguments were wrong and the principle of detailed balance is valid for polyatomic molecules.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Nevertheless, the extended semi-detailed balance conditions invented by Boltzmann in this discussion remain the remarkable generalization of the detailed balance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Here, the reverse reactions with positive constants are included in the list separately.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] We need this separation of direct and reverse reactions to apply later the general formalism to the systems with some irreversible reactions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The system of stoichiometric equations of elementary reactions is the *reaction mechanism*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The *stoichiometric vector* $\gamma _{r}$ is the *r*th row of ${\boldsymbol {\Gamma }}$ with coordinates $\gamma _{ri}=\beta _{ri}-\alpha _{ri}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] According to the *generalized mass action law*, the reaction rate for an elementary reaction is $w_{r}=k_{r}\prod _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{\alpha _{ri}}\,,$ where $a_{i}\geq 0$ is the activity (the "effective concentration") of $A_{i}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The reaction mechanism includes reactions with the reaction rate constants $k_{r}>0$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For a reversible reaction, $K_{r}=k_{r}^{+}/k_{r}^{-}$ is the equilibrium constant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance for the generalized mass action law is: For given values $k_{r}$ there exists a positive equilibrium $a_{i}^{\rm {eq}}>0$ that satisfies detailed balance, that is, $w_{r}^{+}=w_{r}^{-}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The following classical result gives the necessary and sufficient conditions for the existence of a positive equilibrium $a_{i}^{\rm {eq}}>0$ with detailed balance (see, for example, the textbook).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In particular, for any cycle in the monomolecular (linear) reactions the product of the reaction rate constants in the clockwise direction is equal to the product of the reaction rate constants in the counterclockwise direction.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The same condition is valid for the reversible Markov processes (it is equivalent to the "no net flow" condition).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The computational aspect of the Wegscheider conditions was studied by D.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The Wegscheider conditions demonstrate that whereas the principle of detailed balance states a local property of equilibrium, it implies the relations between the kinetic constants that are valid for all states far from equilibrium.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] This is possible because a kinetic law is known and relations between the rates of the elementary processes at equilibrium can be transformed into relations between kinetic constants which are used globally.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For the Wegscheider conditions this kinetic law is the law of mass action (or the generalized law of mass action).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] To describe dynamics of the systems that obey the generalized mass action law, one has to represent the activities as functions of the concentrations *cj* and temperature.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The chemical potential can be represented as a function of *c* and *T*, where *c* is the vector of concentrations with components *cj*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For the ideal systems, $\mu _{i}=RT\ln c_{i}+\mu _{i}^{\ominus }$ and $a_{j}=c_{j}$ : the activity is the concentration and the generalized mass action law is the usual law of mass action.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Consider a system in isothermal (*T*=const) isochoric (the volume *V*=const) condition.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For these conditions, the Helmholtz free energy ⁠ $F(T,V,N)$ ⁠ measures the "useful" work obtainable from a system.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] It is a functions of the temperature *T*, the volume *V* and the amounts of chemical components *Nj* (usually measured in moles), *N* is the vector with components *Nj*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The chemical potential is a partial derivative: $\mu _{i}=\partial F(T,V,N)/\partial N_{i}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Let the principle of detailed balance be valid.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] These symmetry relations, $L_{ij}=L_{ji}$ , are exactly the Onsager reciprocal relations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The coefficient matrix L is non-positive.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] It is negative on the linear span of the stoichiometric vectors $\gamma _{r}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] So, the Onsager relations follow from the principle of detailed balance in the linear approximation near equilibrium.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] There need not be a (global) detailed balance as reservoirs can have different temperatures, chemical potentials, etc.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In mathematical terms, the condition of local detailed balance assures that the logarithmic ratio of the probability of a trajectory to the probability of the time-reversed trajectory equals the entropy flux per *k*B to the system environment.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] It is important here that the environment consists of mutually separated thermodynamic equilibrium baths.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] In particular, local detailed balance allows identification of currents and entropy flows, and is directly related to the so-called fluctuation theorems for entropy fluxes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] As shown in a series of publications, local detailed balance implies detailed, integrated, local, steady-state or transient fluctuation theorems for the entropy flux satisfying a Gallavotti–Cohen-like symmetry.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Discussions and derivations of local detailed balance are found in.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Not all models that are commonly used in nonequilibrium statistical mechanics satisfy local detailed balance, which makes it less evident how to associate heat and entropy fluxes to the proposed dynamics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] To formulate the principle of semi-detailed balance, it is convenient to count the direct and inverse elementary reactions separately.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Let Y be the set of all these vectors $\alpha _{r},\beta _{r}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] $r\in R_{\nu }^{+}$ if and only if $\nu$ is the vector of the input stoichiometric coefficients $\alpha _{r}$ for the *r*th elementary reaction; $r\in R_{\nu }^{-}$ if and only if $\nu$ is the vector of the output stoichiometric coefficients $\beta _{r}$ for the *r*th elementary reaction.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For the Markov kinetics the semi-detailed balance condition is just the elementary balance equation and holds for any steady state.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For the nonlinear mass action law it is, in general, sufficient but not necessary condition for stationarity.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The semi-detailed balance condition is weaker than the detailed balance one: if the principle of detailed balance holds then the condition of semi-detailed balance also holds.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Boltzmann introduced the semi-detailed balance condition for collisions in 1887 and proved that it guaranties the positivity of the entropy production.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For chemical kinetics, this condition (as the *complex balance* condition) was introduced by Horn and Jackson in 1972.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The microscopic backgrounds for the semi-detailed balance were found in the Markov microkinetics of the intermediate compounds that are present in small amounts and whose concentrations are in quasiequilibrium with the main components.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Under these microscopic assumptions, the semi-detailed balance condition is just the balance equation for the Markov microkinetics according to the **Michaelis–Menten–Stueckelberg theorem**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The exponential term is called the *Boltzmann factor* and the multiplier $\varphi _{r}\geq 0$ is the kinetic factor.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For $\lambda =1$ it is just the sum of the reaction rates.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The function $\theta (\lambda )$ is convex because $\theta ''(\lambda )\geq 0$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Direct calculation gives that according to the kinetic equations ${\frac {dF}{dt}}=-VRT\left.{\frac {d\theta (\lambda )}{d\lambda }}\right|_{\lambda =1}$ This is *the general dissipation formula for the generalized mass action law*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The semi-detailed balance condition can be transformed into identity $\theta (0)\equiv \theta (1)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Therefore, for the systems with semi-detailed balance ${dF}/{dt}\leq 0$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] The **cone theorem** states that for the given reaction mechanism and given positive equilibrium, the velocity (*dN/dt*) at a state *N* for a system with complex balance belongs to the cone $\mathbf {Q} _{\rm {DB}}(N)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] That is, there exists a system with detailed balance, the same reaction mechanism, the same positive equilibrium, that gives the same velocity at state *N*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] According to cone theorem, for a given state *N*, the set of velocities of the semidetailed balance systems coincides with the set of velocities of the detailed balance systems if their reaction mechanisms and equilibria coincide.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] Detailed balance states that in equilibrium each elementary process is equilibrated by its reverse process and requires reversibility of all elementary processes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For many real physico-chemical complex systems (e.g. homogeneous combustion, heterogeneous catalytic oxidation, most enzyme reactions etc.), detailed mechanisms include both reversible and irreversible reactions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] If one represents irreversible reactions as limits of reversible steps, then it becomes obvious that not all reaction mechanisms with irreversible reactions can be obtained as limits of systems or reversible reactions with detailed balance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/detailed-balance] For example, the irreversible cycle ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 -> A1}}$ cannot be obtained as such a limit but the reaction mechanism ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 <- A1}}$ can.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In mathematics, especially in ergodic theory, **ergodicity** is a way of saying that a dynamical system behaves as one indivisible statistical system, rather than being composed of statistically distinguishable subsystems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] More precisely, a measure-preserving dynamical system is ergodic if every invariant measurable set has either measure zero or full measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Equivalently, the system cannot be decomposed, up to sets of measure zero, into two smaller invariant parts of positive measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodic theorems relate this condition to the equality of time averages and space averages.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Under suitable hypotheses, the time average of an observable along almost every orbit is equal to its space average.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodicity itself, however, is not the same as randomness, mixing, chaos, or the assertion that every individual orbit visits every part of the space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodicity may also be described in terms of ergodic measures: an invariant probability measure is ergodic if it cannot be decomposed into a nontrivial convex combination of other invariant probability measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodic systems occur in many areas of physics, geometry, probability theory, and dynamical systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The origins of the subject lie in statistical physics, where Ludwig Boltzmann formulated the ergodic hypothesis in connection with the foundations of statistical mechanics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodicity is a way of saying that a system has no hidden division into smaller statistically separate parts.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If the system is observed for a long time, its long-run statistical behavior is governed by one invariant measure, rather than by a choice among several different invariant components.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A simple example comes from coin tossing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Suppose the same biased coin is tossed forever, with probability p of heads on each toss.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The resulting stationary process is ergodic: apart from events of probability zero, there is no further permanent statistical label attached to the sequence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In particular, the long-run frequency of heads is p for almost every sequence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] By contrast, suppose that before any tosses are made, one of two coins is chosen at random: one coin has probability $p_{1}$ of heads, and the other has probability $p_{2}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This process is stationary, but it is not ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The hidden choice of coin is an invariant fact about the whole infinite sequence, and it separates the process into two statistically different components.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In a measure-preserving dynamical system, this idea is expressed by saying that every invariant measurable set has either measure zero or full measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Equivalently, the system cannot be decomposed, up to sets of measure zero, into two invariant parts of positive measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodicity is related to the equality of time averages and space averages through ergodic theorems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] It should not be confused with randomness, mixing, chaos, or the claim that every individual orbit visits every part of the space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Another basic example comes from rotations of the circle.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Let $R_{\alpha }$ be the rotation of the circle through the angle $2\pi \alpha$ radians.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] After n iterations, a point has been rotated by $2\pi n\alpha$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If $\alpha$ is rational, say $\alpha =p/q$ in lowest terms, then every point is periodic: after q iterations it returns to its original position.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] With respect to Lebesgue measure on the circle, this rotation is not ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] is invariant under the rotation, since replacing $\theta$ by $\theta +2\pi p/q$ does not change $\cos(q\theta )$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The circle can thus be divided into smaller invariant pieces, such as $a<\cos(q\theta )<b$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If $\alpha$ is irrational, the orbit of every point is dense in the circle.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In fact, the irrational rotation is ergodic with respect to Lebesgue measure: every measurable set that is invariant under the rotation has either measure zero or full measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Thus the system has many different individual orbits, but it has no nontrivial measurable decomposition into invariant statistical components.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This example also shows that ergodicity is weaker than mixing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Irrational rotations are ergodic, but they are not mixing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the measure-theoretic definition of ergodicity, the basic data are a measure space X , and a time-evolution of its points.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the coin-toss example, the state space may be taken to be the space of infinite sequences of outcomes, and the time evolution is the shift map on this space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the rotation example, the state space is the circle, and the time evolution is repeated application of the rotation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Both are examples of discrete time dynamical systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The elements of the space X are possible states of the system.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A measurable set is a collection of states to which the theory assigns a measure, such as length, area, volume, or probability.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The space X is equipped with a sigma-algebra ${\mathcal {B}}$ of sets that are allowed to be measured.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] When X is a topological space, such as an interval, a circle, or a manifold, the usual choice is often the Borel sigma-algebra, generated by the open sets.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In probability examples, measurable sets are events.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] For instance, in an infinite sequence of coin tosses, the event "the first toss is heads" is measurable, as is the event "the long-run frequency of heads exists and is equal to p ".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A set is invariant if membership in it is unchanged by the time evolution, up to sets of measure zero.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A (discrete time) measure preserving system is thus the pair $(X,T)$ where X is a measure space and T is a measure-preserving transformation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] An invariant measurable set represents a statistical property of the state that persists under the dynamics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodicity says that every such persistent measurable property is trivial: it holds either almost nowhere (i.e., only on a set of measure zero) or almost everywhere (i.e., everywhere except a set of measure zero).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The original motivation for ergodicity came from statistical mechanics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In classical mechanics, the state of a system is represented by a point in phase space: for example, the positions and momenta of all particles in a gas.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The time evolution of the system moves this point through phase space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Hamiltonian flow preserves the natural phase-space volume, called Liouville measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] After restricting to an energy surface, this gives the measure underlying the microcanonical ensemble.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The physical question was whether long-time averages along the actual motion of one system can be replaced by averages over the corresponding energy surface.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] agrees, for typical initial states x , representing the state of the large number of particles in the gas, with the average of f over the energy surface.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The ergodic hypothesis was an early attempt to justify this replacement.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In modern measure-theoretic language, ergodicity does not mean that a trajectory literally passes through every point of the energy surface.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Rather, it means that, relative to the chosen invariant measure, there is no further invariant measurable decomposition of the system into smaller statistical components.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Under suitable hypotheses, ergodic theorems then imply the equality of time averages and space averages for many observables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The term *ergodic* is usually attributed to Ludwig Boltzmann and is commonly explained as a combination of the Greek words ἔργον (*ergon*, "work") and ὁδός (*hodos*, "path").
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The exact historical development of the term is not entirely straightforward; it has also been connected with Boltzmann's term *ergomonode*, used in his work on statistical mechanics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The concept arose in the attempt to justify the use of statistical methods in statistical mechanics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In that setting, one wants to relate time averages along the motion of a mechanical system to averages over a space of possible states.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This motivation led to the ergodic hypothesis, according to which a mechanical system may, under suitable assumptions, be treated as if its long-time behavior samples the relevant state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The original physical form of the hypothesis was later replaced by more precise mathematical notions in ergodic theory, especially the measure-theoretic definition in terms of invariant measurable sets.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In 1913, Michel Plancherel showed that one natural formulation of the classical mechanical ergodic hypothesis could not hold as originally stated.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodicity appears in several related settings in physics and geometry.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In each case, one must specify both the state space and the invariant measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The common measure-theoretic question is whether the system has nontrivial invariant measurable subsets.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In statistical mechanics, ergodicity is used to justify replacing long-time averages of observables by averages over an invariant ensemble.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] For isolated Hamiltonian systems, the relevant ensemble is usually the microcanonical ensemble on an energy surface.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This is the setting of the classical ergodic hypothesis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Rigorous proofs of ergodicity for realistic many-particle systems are difficult.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Important mathematical examples come from dynamical billiards, where idealized particle collisions provide systems for which ergodicity can sometimes be proved.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Basic examples of ergodic and non-ergodic systems occur already in low-dimensional dynamics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Irrational rotations of the circle are ergodic with respect to Lebesgue measure, but they are not mixing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Other standard examples include the baker's map, Arnold's cat map, Bernoulli shifts, and certain billiard systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] These examples illustrate different relations between ergodicity, mixing, entropy, and chaotic behavior.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodic flows also arise naturally in geometry.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A central example is the geodesic flow on a Riemannian manifold, usually considered on the unit tangent bundle with its natural invariant measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] On a flat torus, motion in a fixed irrational direction is dense on the torus and is ergodic after restricting to that direction.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The full geodesic flow on the unit tangent bundle is not ergodic, since the direction of motion is conserved.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] By contrast, the geodesic flow on a compact Riemannian manifold of negative curvature is ergodic with respect to the natural invariant measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This provides one of the classical families of examples in ergodic theory and is closely related to Anosov flows.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Other geometric examples include horocycle flows, flows on translation surfaces, and billiard flows.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In these settings, ergodicity concerns invariant measurable subsets of the appropriate phase space, not whether a single path literally passes through every point.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In quantum mechanics, the word ergodicity is used more cautiously, since quantum evolution is not described by point trajectories in classical phase space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Related notions appear in quantum chaos and in the quantum ergodicity theorem, which concerns the distribution of eigenfunctions in a semiclassical limit.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] These ideas are related to, but not identical with, classical measure-theoretic ergodicity.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodic measures provide one of the cornerstones with which ergodicity is generally discussed.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Let $(X,{\mathcal {B}})$ be a measurable space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If T is a measurable function from X to itself and $\mu$ a probability measure on $(X,{\mathcal {B}})$ , then a measure-preserving dynamical system is defined as a dynamical system for which $\mu {\mathord {\left(T^{-1}(A)\right)}}=\mu (A)$ for all $A\in {\mathcal {B}}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Such a T is said to preserve ${\displaystyle \mu$ equivalently, that $\mu$ is T -invariant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In other words, there are no T -invariant subsets up to measure 0 (with respect to $\mu$ ).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Some authors relax the requirement that T preserves $\mu$ to the requirement that T is a non-singular transformation with respect to $\mu$ , meaning that N is a subset of measure zero if and only if $T^{-1}(N)$ is.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The simplest example is when X is a finite set and $\mu$ is the normalized counting measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Then a self-map of X preserves $\mu$ if and only if it is a bijection, and it is ergodic if and only if T has only one orbit (that is, for every $x,y\in X$ there exists $k\in \mathbb {N}$ such that $y=T^{k}(x)$ ).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Let S be a finite set and $X=S^{\mathbb {Z} }$ with $\mu$ the product measure (each factor S being endowed with its normalized counting measure).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] There are many more ergodic measures for the shift map T on X .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Periodic sequences give finitely supported measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] More interestingly, there are infinitely-supported ones which are subshifts of finite type.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Let X be the unit circle $\{z\in \mathbb {C} ,\,|z|=1\}$ , with its Lebesgue measure $\mu$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] For any $\theta \in \mathbb {R}$ the rotation of X of angle $\theta$ is given by $T_{\theta }(z)=e^{2i\pi \theta }z$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If $\theta =p/q$ is rational, then $T_{\theta }$ is not ergodic for Lebesgue measure; for example, the nonconstant function $z\mapsto z^{q}$ is invariant under the rotation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] On the other hand, if $\theta$ is irrational then $T_{\theta }$ is ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Then any element $g\in \mathrm {SL} _{2}(\mathbb {Z} )$ defines a self-map of X since $g\left(\mathbb {Z} ^{2}\right)=\mathbb {Z} ^{2}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] When ${\textstyle g=\left({\begin{array}{cc}2&1\\1&1\end{array}}\right)}$ one obtains the so-called Arnold's cat map, which is ergodic for the Lebesgue measure on the torus.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If $\mu$ is a probability measure on a space X which is ergodic for a transformation T the pointwise ergodic theorem of G.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Birkhoff states that for every integrable function $f:X\to \mathbb {R}$ and for $\mu$ -almost every point $x\in X$ the time average on the orbit of x converges to the space average of f .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The mean ergodic theorem of J. von Neumann is a similar, weaker statement about averaged translates of square-integrable functions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] For a continuous transformation of a second-countable topological space with a Borel probability measure $\mu$ , ergodicity implies that $\mu$ -almost every orbit is dense in the support of $\mu$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Explicit examples can be constructed with shift-invariant measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The topological counterpart to ergodicity is a minimal dynamical system, in which the orbit of every point is dense.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A measure-preserving system is called mixing if sets become asymptotically independent under iteration.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Mixing implies ergodicity under standard hypotheses.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The converse is not true, for example a rotation with irrational angle on the circle (which is ergodic per the examples above) is not mixing (for a sufficiently small interval its successive images will not intersect itself most of the time).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Bernoulli shifts are mixing, and so is Arnold's cat map.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] It is immediate that a mixing transformation is also ergodic (taking A to be a T -stable subset and B its complement).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Kolmogorov–Sinai entropy is another invariant of measure-preserving systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] It measures the average information produced by the dynamics, rather than whether the system decomposes into invariant measurable components.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Thus entropy and ergodicity answer different questions: an ergodic system may have zero entropy, while positive entropy alone does not imply ergodicity unless one restricts to an ergodic component.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The transformation T is said to be *properly ergodic* if it does not have an orbit of full measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the discrete case this means that the measure $\mu$ is not supported on a finite orbit of T .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The definition is essentially the same for continuous-time dynamical systems as for a single transformation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] As in the discrete case the simplest example is that of a transitive action, for instance the action on the circle given by $T_{t}(z)=e^{2i\pi t}z$ is ergodic for Lebesgue measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] An example with infinitely many orbits is given by the flow along an irrational slope on the torus: let $X=\mathbb {S} ^{1}\times \mathbb {S} ^{1}$ and $\alpha \in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If X is a compact metric space it is naturally endowed with the σ-algebra of Borel sets.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The additional structure coming from the topology then allows a much more detailed theory for ergodic transformations and measures on X .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A very powerful alternate characterization of ergodic measures can be given using the theory of Banach spaces.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The signed Radon measures on X form a Banach space, of which the set ${\mathcal {P}}(X)$ of probability measures on X is a convex subset.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Given a continuous transformation T of X , the subset ${\mathcal {P}}(X)^{T}$ of T -invariant measures is a closed convex subset, and a measure is ergodic for T if and only if it is an extreme point of this convex set.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the setting above, the Krylov–Bogolyubov argument shows that ${\mathcal {P}}(X)^{T}$ is nonempty.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] It is also compact and convex in the weak-* topology; hence by the Krein–Milman theorem it has extreme points.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Therefore a continuous transformation of a compact metric space always admits ergodic measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In general an invariant measure need not be ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the compact metric setting, Choquet theory applied to the compact convex set ${\mathcal {P}}(X)^{T}$ of invariant probability measures implies that an invariant measure can be expressed as the barycenter of a probability measure supported on the set of ergodic measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This is referred to as the *ergodic decomposition* of the measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the case of $X=\{1,\ldots ,n\}$ and $T=(1\,2)(3\,4\,\cdots \,n)$ the normalized counting measure is not ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The ergodic measures for T are the uniform measures $\mu _{1},\mu _{2}$ supported on the subsets $\{1,2\}$ and $\{3,\ldots ,n\}$ , and every T -invariant probability measure can be written in the form $t\mu _{1}+(1-t)\mu _{2}$ for some $t\in [0,1]$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In particular ${\textstyle {\frac {2}{n}}\mu _{1}+{\frac {n-2}{n}}\mu _{2}}$ is the ergodic decomposition of the normalized counting measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The same functional-analytic interpretation applies to continuous actions of $\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {R} _{+}$ on compact metric spaces, with invariant measures taken with respect to the corresponding flow or semigroup.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The transformation T is said to be **uniquely ergodic** if there is a unique T -invariant Borel probability measure $\mu$ on X .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In the examples considered above, irrational rotations of the circle are uniquely ergodic; shift maps are not.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If $\left(X_{n}\right)_{n\geq 1}$ is a discrete-time stochastic process with state space S , its joint distribution defines a probability measure on the path space $S^{\mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A stationary process is said to be ergodic if this shift-invariant probability measure is ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Equivalently, every shift-invariant event has probability zero or one.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This is a particular case of the notions discussed above.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The simplest case is that of an independent and identically distributed process, which corresponds to a product measure on the path space and is ergodic for the shift map.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Another important case is that of a stationary Markov chain, which is discussed in detail below.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A similar interpretation holds for continuous-time stochastic processes, though the construction of the measurable structure of the action is more complicated.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A Markov chain on S is defined by a matrix $P\in [0,1]^{S\times S}$ , where $P(s_{1},s_{2})$ is the transition probability from $s_{1}$ to $s_{2}$ , so for every $s\in S$ we have ${\textstyle \sum _{s'\in S}P(s,s')=1}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The measure $\mu _{\nu }$ is ergodic for the shift map if the associated finite Markov chain is irreducible, that is, if any state can be reached with positive probability from any other state in a finite number of steps.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] For a finite irreducible Markov chain, there is a unique stationary measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A stronger sufficient condition, often used to ensure convergence to the stationary measure, is that 1 be a simple eigenvalue of the matrix P and that all other eigenvalues of P in $\mathbb {C}$ have modulus less than 1 .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Note that in probability theory a finite Markov chain is often called ergodic if it is irreducible and aperiodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Aperiodicity is not necessary for the associated shift-invariant measure $\mu _{\nu }$ to be ergodic; it is instead related to stronger convergence and mixing properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Hence the notion of "ergodicity" for a Markov chain and the notion of ergodicity for the associated shift-invariant measure are closely related but not identical.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If $P(s,s')=1/|S|$ for all $s,s'\in S$ , then the stationary measure on S is the uniform probability measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The corresponding measure $\mu _{\nu }$ on $S^{\mathbb {Z} }$ is the product of uniform probability measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This gives the Bernoulli shift example from above.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Markov chains with more than one recurrent communicating class are not irreducible, and the associated stationary shift measures need not be ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If $S_{1},S_{2}\subsetneq S$ are two distinct recurrent communicating classes, there are stationary measures $\nu _{1},\nu _{2}$ supported on $S_{1},S_{2}$ respectively.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The corresponding shift-invariant measures on $S^{\mathbb {Z} }$ are ergodic on their separate components, but a nontrivial convex combination of them is not ergodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Thus it is not ergodic in the aperiodic Markov-chain sense, although the associated measure $\mu$ on $\{1,2\}^{\mathbb {Z} }$ is ergodic for the shift map.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] However, the shift is not mixing for this measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The definition of ergodicity extends from a single transformation to group actions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Let G be a group acting measurably on a measure space $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu )$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Equivalently, every invariant measurable set is either null or conull.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The classical cases of a single invertible transformation and a continuous-time flow correspond to actions of $\mathbb {Z}$ and $\mathbb {R}$ , respectively.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The same definition also applies to non-abelian groups.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] If the action does not preserve $\mu$ but preserves its measure class, so that null sets are carried to null sets, then $\mu$ is called quasi-invariant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In that setting, the action is called ergodic if every measurable set that is invariant modulo null sets is either null or conull.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Important examples include actions of semisimple Lie groups and their lattices, such as boundary actions on Furstenberg boundaries.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The same terminology is also used for measurable equivalence relations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] A measurable equivalence relation is said to be ergodic if every saturated measurable subset is either null or conull.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Ergodicity also has a representation-theoretic formulation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Let G be a group and let $\pi :G\to U({\mathcal {H}})$ be a unitary representation on a Hilbert space ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This condition can also be expressed in terms of matrix coefficients.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Matrix coefficients of unitary representations are weakly almost periodic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] This terminology is compatible with the usual notion of ergodicity for measure-preserving actions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Suppose that G acts on a probability space $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu )$ by measure-preserving transformations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] The action of G is ergodic if and only if the only G -invariant functions in $L^{2}(X,\mu )$ are the constant functions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] Then the action is ergodic if and only if the restricted Koopman representation on $L_{0}^{2}(X,\mu )$ is ergodic in the representation-theoretic sense, meaning that it has no nonzero invariant vector.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] For a single invertible transformation T , this is the same statement for the unitary operator $U_{T}f=f\circ T^{-1}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/ergodicity] In this language, ergodicity means that the eigenspace for the eigenvalue 1 consists only of the constant functions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In statistics, **Markov chain Monte Carlo** (**MCMC**) is a class of algorithms used to draw samples from a probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Given a probability distribution, one can construct a Markov chain whose elements' distribution approximates it, i.e. the Markov chain's equilibrium distribution matches the target distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more steps that are included, the more closely the distribution of the sample matches the actual desired distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are used to study probability distributions that are too complex or too high dimensional to study with analytic techniques alone.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Various algorithms exist for constructing such Markov chains, including the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods create samples from a continuous random variable, with probability density proportional to a known function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These samples can be used to evaluate an integral over that variable, as its expected value or variance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Practically, an ensemble of chains is generally developed, starting from a set of points arbitrarily chosen and sufficiently distant from each other.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These chains are stochastic processes of "walkers" which move around randomly according to an algorithm that looks for places with a reasonably high contribution to the integral to move into next, assigning them higher probabilities.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Random walk Monte Carlo methods are a kind of random simulation or Monte Carlo method.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, whereas the random samples of the integrand used in a conventional Monte Carlo integration are statistically independent, those used in MCMC are autocorrelated.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Correlations of samples introduces the need to use the Markov chain central limit theorem when estimating the error of mean values.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms create Markov chains such that they have an equilibrium distribution which is proportional to the function given.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The development of MCMC methods is deeply rooted in the early exploration of Monte Carlo (MC) techniques in the mid-20th century, particularly in physics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These developments were marked by the Metropolis algorithm proposed by Nicholas Metropolis, Arianna W.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Teller, and Edward Teller in 1953, which was designed to tackle high-dimensional integration problems using early computers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Hastings generalized this algorithm and inadvertently introduced the component-wise updating idea, later known as Gibbs sampling.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Simultaneously, the theoretical foundations for Gibbs sampling were being developed, such as the Hammersley–Clifford theorem from Julian Besag's 1974 paper.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Although the seeds of MCMC were sown earlier, including the formal naming of Gibbs sampling in image processing by Stuart Geman and Donald Geman (1984) and the data augmentation method by Martin A.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This transformation was accompanied by significant theoretical advancements, such as Luke Tierney's (1994) rigorous treatment of MCMC convergence, and Jun S.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Liu, Wong, and Augustine Kong's (1994, 1995) analysis of Gibbs sampler structure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Subsequent developments further expanded the MCMC toolkit, including particle filters (Sequential Monte Carlo) for sequential problems, Perfect sampling aiming for exact simulation (Jim Propp and David B.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Green, 1995) for handling variable-dimension models, and deeper investigations into convergence diagnostics and the central limit theorem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overall, the evolution of MCMC represents a paradigm shift in statistical computation, enabling the analysis of numerous previously intractable complex models and continually expanding the scope and impact of statistics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose *(Xn)* is a Markov Chain in the general state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ with specific properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Particularly, we hope to establish the Law of Large Numbers and the Central Limit Theorem for MCMC.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the following, we state some definitions and theorems necessary for the important convergence results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In short, we need the existence of invariant measure and Harris recurrent to establish the Law of Large Numbers of MCMC (Ergodic Theorem).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] And we need aperiodicity, irreducibility and extra conditions such as reversibility to ensure the Central Limit Theorem holds in MCMC.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recall that in the discrete setting, a Markov chain is said to be *irreducible* if it is possible to reach any state from any other state in a finite number of steps with positive probability.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in the continuous setting, point-to-point transitions have zero probability.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, **φ-irreducibility** generalizes irreducibility by using a reference measure φ on the measurable space $({\mathcal {X}},{\mathcal {B}}({\mathcal {X}}))$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is a more general definition for irreducibility of a Markov chain in non-discrete state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the discrete case, an irreducible Markov chain is said to be *aperiodic* if it has period 1.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **Harris recurrent** if there exists a measure $\psi$ such that the chain is $\psi$ -irreducible and every measurable set A with $\psi (A)>0$ is Harris recurrent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This definition is only needed when the state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ is uncountable.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the countable case, recurrence corresponds to $\mathbb {E} _{x}[\eta _{x}]=\infty$ , which is equivalent to $P_{x}(\tau _{x}<\infty )=1$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When there exists an *invariant probability measure* for a **ψ-irreducible** (hence recurrent) chain, the chain is said to be **positive recurrent**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recurrent chains that do not allow for a finite invariant measure are called **null recurrent**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In applications of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), a very useful criterion for Harris recurrence involves the use of bounded harmonic functions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These functions are *invariant* under the transition kernel in the functional sense, and they help characterize Harris recurrence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This theorem provides a fundamental justification for the use of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, and it serves as the counterpart of the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) in classical Monte Carlo.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] An important aspect of this result is that $\pi$ does not need to be a probability measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Therefore, there can be some type of strong stability even if the chain is null recurrent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Moreover, the Markov chain can be started from arbitrary state.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is the Ergodic Theorem that we are more familiar with.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are several conditions under which the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) holds for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One of the most commonly used is the condition of **reversibility**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A stationary Markov chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **reversible** if the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+2}=x$ is the same as the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n}=x$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] for every pair $(x,y)$ in the state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Even though reversibility is a restrictive assumption in theory, it is often easily satisfied in practical MCMC algorithms by introducing auxiliary variables or using symmetric proposal mechanisms.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are many other conditions that can be used to establish CLT for MCMC such as geometric ergodicity and the discrete state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods produce autocorrelated samples, in contrast to standard Monte Carlo techniques that draw independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Autocorrelation means successive draws from the Markov chain are statistically dependent, so each new sample adds less fresh information than an independent draw would.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As a result, one must account for this correlation when assessing the accuracy of estimates from the chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In particular, positive autocorrelation in the chain increases the variance of estimators and slows the convergence of sample averages toward the true expectation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effect of correlation on estimation can be quantified through the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For a chain targeting a distribution with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of the sample mean after N steps is approximately ${\sigma ^{2}}{\big /}N_{\text{eff}}$ , where $N_{\text{eff}}$ is an effective sample size smaller than N .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The term in parentheses, $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}$ , is often called the integrated autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When the chain has no autocorrelation ( $\rho _{k}=0$ for all $k\geq 1$ ), this factor equals 1, and one recovers the usual $\sigma ^{2}/N$ variance for independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the chain's samples are highly correlated, the sum of autocorrelations is large, leading to a much bigger variance for ${\bar {X}}_{N}$ than in the independent case.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effective sample size $N_{\text{eff}}$ is a useful diagnostic that translates the autocorrelation in a chain into an equivalent number of independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] so that $N_{\text{eff}}$ is the number of independent draws that would yield the same estimation precision as the N dependent draws from the Markov chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, if $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}=5$ , then $N_{\text{eff}}=N/5$ , meaning the chain of length N carries information equivalent to $N/5$ independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In an ideal scenario with no correlation, $\rho _{k}=0$ and thus $N_{\text{eff}}\approx N$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] But in a poorly mixing chain with strong autocorrelation, $N_{\text{eff}}$ can be much smaller than N .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, monitoring the ESS for each parameter is a way to gauge how much correlation is present: a low ESS indicates that many more iterations may be needed to achieve a desired effective sample of independent draws.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to address this problem could be shortening the steps of the walker, so that it does not continuously try to exit the highest probability region, though this way the process would be highly autocorrelated and expensive (i.e. many steps would be required for an accurate result).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] More sophisticated methods such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo and the Wang and Landau algorithm use various ways of reducing this autocorrelation, while managing to keep the process in the regions that give a higher contribution to the integral.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms usually rely on a more complicated theory and are harder to implement, but they usually converge faster.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] We outline several general strategies such as reparameterization, adaptive proposal tuning, parameter blocking, and overrelaxation that help reduce correlation and improve sampling efficiency within the standard MCMC framework.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to reduce autocorrelation is to reformulate or reparameterize the statistical model so that the posterior geometry leads to more efficient sampling.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By changing the coordinate system or using alternative variable definitions, one can often lessen correlations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, in Bayesian hierarchical modeling, a non-centered parameterization can be used in place of the standard (centered) formulation to avoid extreme posterior correlations between latent and higher-level parameters.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This involves expressing latent variables in terms of independent auxiliary variables, dramatically improving mixing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Such reparameterization strategies are commonly employed in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithm to enhance convergence and reduce autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Another approach to reducing correlation is to improve the MCMC proposal mechanism.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, step size tuning is critical: if the proposed steps are too small, the sampler moves slowly and produces highly correlated samples; if the steps are too large, many proposals are rejected, resulting in repeated values.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adjusting the proposal step size during an initial testing phase helps find a balance where the sampler explores the space efficiently without too many rejections.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adaptive MCMC methods modify proposal distributions based on the chain's past samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm updates the Gaussian proposal distribution using the full information accumulated from the chain so far, allowing the proposal to adapt over time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is a technique that reduces autocorrelation in MCMC by updating parameters jointly rather than one at a time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When parameters exhibit strong posterior correlations, one-by-one updates can lead to poor mixing and slow exploration of the target distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By identifying and sampling blocks of correlated parameters together, the sampler can more effectively traverse high-density regions of the posterior.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is commonly used in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithms.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In blocked Gibbs sampling, entire groups of variables are updated conditionally at each step.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings, multivariate proposals enable joint updates (i.e., updates of multiple parameters at once using a vector-valued proposal distribution, typically a multivariate Gaussian), though they often require careful tuning of the proposal covariance matrix.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is a technique to reduce autocorrelation between successive samples by proposing new samples that are negatively correlated with the current state.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This helps the chain explore the posterior more efficiently, especially in high-dimensional Gaussian models or when using Gibbs sampling.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The basic idea is to reflect the current sample across the conditional mean, producing proposals that retain the correct stationary distribution but with reduced serial dependence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is particularly effective when combined with Gaussian conditional distributions, where exact reflection or partial overrelaxation can be analytically implemented.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting MCMC methodologies are a class of mean-field particle methods for obtaining random samples from a sequence of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In principle, any Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler can be turned into an interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers can be interpreted as a way to run in parallel a sequence of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, interacting simulated annealing algorithms are based on independent Metropolis–Hastings moves interacting sequentially with a selection-resampling type mechanism.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In contrast to traditional Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, the precision parameter of this class of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers is *only* related to the number of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These advanced particle methodologies belong to the class of Feynman–Kac particle models, also called Sequential Monte Carlo or particle filter methods in Bayesian inference and signal processing communities.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mutation-selection genetic particle algorithm with Markov chain Monte Carlo mutations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The quasi-Monte Carlo method is an analog to the normal Monte Carlo method that uses low-discrepancy sequences instead of random numbers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] It yields an integration error that decays faster than that of true random sampling, as quantified by the Koksma–Hlawka inequality.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Empirically it allows the reduction of both estimation error and convergence time by an order of magnitude.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain quasi-Monte Carlo methods such as the Array–RQMC method combine randomized quasi–Monte Carlo and Markov chain simulation by simulating n chains simultaneously in a way that better approximates the true distribution of the chain than with ordinary MCMC.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In empirical experiments, the variance of the average of a function of the state sometimes converges at rate $O(n^{-2})$ or even faster, instead of the $O(n^{-1})$ Monte Carlo rate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods are primarily used for calculating numerical approximations of multi-dimensional integrals, for example in Bayesian statistics, computational physics, computational biology and computational linguistics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Bayesian statistics, Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are typically used to calculate moments and credible intervals of posterior probability distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The use of MCMC methods makes it possible to compute large hierarchical models that require integrations over hundreds to thousands of unknown parameters.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Many contemporary research problems in statistical physics can be addressed by approximate solutions using Monte Carlo simulation, which provides valuable insights into the properties of complex systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Monte Carlo methods are fundamental in computational physics, astrophysics, physical chemistry, and related disciplines, with broad applications including medical physics, where they are employed to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead of exhaustively analyzing all possible system states, the Monte Carlo method randomly examines a subset of them to form a representative sample, and yields accurate approximations of the system's characteristic properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As the number of sampled states increases, the error can be further reduced to a lower level.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Langevin Dynamics are typically used in complex distribution sampling and generative modeling, via an MCMC procedure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Specifically, given the probability density function $p(x)$ , we use its log gradient $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ as the score function and start from a prior distribution $x_{0}\sim p_{0}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ and $K\rightarrow \infty$ , $x_{K}$ converges to a sample from the target distribution $p(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For some complex distribution, if we know its probability density function but find it difficult to directly sample from it, we can apply Langevin Dynamics as an alternate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in most cases, especially generative modeling, usually we do not know the exact probability density function of the target distribution we wish to sample from, neither the score function $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, score matching methods provide feasible solutions, minimizing the Fisher information metric between a parameterized score-based model $s_{\theta }(x)$ and the score function without knowing the ground-truth data score.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The score function can be estimated on a training dataset by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In real cases, however, the training data only takes a small region of the target distribution, and the estimated score functions are inaccurate in other low density regions with fewer available data examples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] To overcome this challenge, denoising score matching methods perturb the available data examples with noise of different scales, which can improve the coverage of low density regions, and use them as the training dataset for the score-base model.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Note that the choice of noise scales is tricky, as too large noise will corrupt the original data, while too small noise will not populate the original data to those low density regions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Thus, carefully crafted noise schedules are applied for higher quality generation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Usually it is not hard to construct a Markov chain with the desired properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more difficult problem is to determine (1) when to start collecting statistics and (2) how many steps are needed to converge to the stationary distribution within an acceptable error.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Fortunately, there are a variety of practical diagnostics to empirically assess convergence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Formally, let $\pi$ denote the stationary distribution and $P^{t}(x,\cdot )$ the distribution of the Markov chain after t steps starting from state x .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A chain is said to mix rapidly if $d_{\text{TV}}(P^{t}(x,\cdot ),\pi )\leq \epsilon$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ within a small number of steps t under a pre-defined tolerance $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In other words, the stationary distribution is reached quickly starting from an arbitrary position, and the minimum such t is known as the mixing time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, however, the total variation distance is generally intractable to compute, especially in high-dimensional problems or when the stationary distribution is only known up to a normalizing constant (as in most Bayesian applications).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Gelman-Rubin statistic, also known as the **potential scale reduction factor (PSRF)**, evaluates MCMC convergence by sampling multiple independent Markov chains and comparing within-chain and between-chain variances.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If all chains have converged to the same stationary distribution, the between-chain and within-chain variances should be similar, and thus the PSRF must approach 1.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, a value of $<1.1$ is often taken as evidence of convergence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Higher values suggest that the chains are still exploring different parts of the target distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Geweke diagnostic examines whether the distribution of samples in the early part of the Markov chain is statistically indistinguishable from the distribution in a later part.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Since MCMC samples are autocorrelated, a simple comparison of sample means is insufficient.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead, the difference in means is standardized using an estimator of the spectral density at zero frequency, which accounts for the long-range dependencies in the chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the long-run variance (i.e., the spectral density at frequency zero), commonly estimated using Newey-West estimators or batch means.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the statistic Z follows an approximately standard normal distribution $Z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If $|Z|>1.96$ , the null hypothesis is rejected at the 5% significance level, suggesting that the chain has not yet reached stationarity.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Heidelberger-Welch diagnostic is grounded in spectral analysis and Brownian motion theory, and is particularly useful in the early stages of simulation to determine appropriate burn-in and stopping time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The diagnostic consists of two components, a **stationarity test** that assesses whether the Markov chain has reached a steady-state, and a **half-width test** that determines whether the estimated expectation is within a user-specified precision.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let $\{X_{t}\}_{t=1}^{n}$ be the output of an MCMC simulation for a scalar function $g(X_{t})$ , and $g_{1},g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}$ the evaluations of the function g over the chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\bar {g}}_{n}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}g_{i}$ is the sample mean and ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the spectral density at frequency zero.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the process $B_{n}(t)$ converges in distribution to a Brownian bridge.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This statistic is compared against known critical values from the Brownian bridge distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the null hypothesis is rejected, the first 10% of the samples are discarded and the test can be repeated on the remaining chain until either stationarity is accepted or 50% of the chain is discarded.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Once stationarity is accepted, the second part of the diagnostic checks whether the Monte Carlo estimator is accurate enough for practical use.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is an estimate of the variance of $g(X)$ , $t_{\alpha /2,\nu }$ is the Student's t critical value at confidence level $1-\alpha$ and degrees of freedom $\nu$ , n is the number of samples used.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the half-width is smaller than a user-defined tolerance (e.g., 0.05), the chain is considered long enough to estimate the expectation reliably.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Otherwise, the simulation should be extended.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is specifically designed to assess how many iterations are needed to estimate quantiles or tail probabilities of the target distribution with a desired accuracy and confidence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Unlike Gelman-Rubin or Geweke diagnostics, which are based on assessing convergence to the entire distribution, the Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is goal-oriented as it provides estimates for the number of samples required to estimate a specific quantile of interest within a desired margin of error.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let q denote the desired quantile (e.g., 0.025) of a real-valued function $g(X)$ : in other words, the goal is to find u such that $P(g(X)\leq u)=q$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose we wish to estimate this quantile such that the estimate falls within margin $\varepsilon$ of the true value with probability $1-\alpha$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $I(\cdot )$ is the indicator function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The sequence $\{W_{n}\}$ is treated as a realization from a two-state Markov chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] While this may not be strictly true, it is often a good approximation in practice.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $\Phi ^{-1}(\cdot )$ is the standard normal quantile function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and non-uniform random variate generation, available for modeling phenomena with significant input uncertainties, e.g. risk assessments for nuclear power plants.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] They can provide approximate solutions to problems too complex for mathematical analysis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The name comes from the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, where the primary developer of the method, mathematician Stanisław Ulam, was inspired by his uncle's gambling habits.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, engineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] They have also been applied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political science.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scientific and technological breakthroughs.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the curse of dimensionality, the reliability of random number generators, and the verification and validation of the results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Generate inputs randomly from a probability distribution over the domain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Perform a deterministic computation of the outputs.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] For example, consider a quadrant (circular sector) inscribed in a unit square.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Uniformly scatter a given number of points over the square.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance from the origin of less than 1.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate of the ratio of the two areas, ⁠π/4⁠.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes the quadrant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it falls within the quadrant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Aggregating the results yields our final result, the approximation of π.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the whole square.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and their use benefitted greatly from pseudorandom number generators, which are far quicker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously employed.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often used in physical and mathematical problems and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other approaches.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs such as the calculation of risk in business and, in mathematics, evaluation of multidimensional definite integrals with complicated boundary conditions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In application to systems engineering problems (space, oil exploration, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo–based predictions of failure, cost overruns and schedule overruns are routinely better than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem having a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] By the law of large numbers, integrals described by the expected value of some random variable can be approximated by taking the empirical mean (a.k.a. the 'sample mean') of independent samples of the variable.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] When the probability distribution of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The central idea is to design a judicious Markov chain model with a prescribed stationary probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] That is, in the limit, the samples being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (target) distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] By the ergodic theorem, the stationary distribution is approximated by the empirical measures of the random states of the MCMC sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] These flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the distributions of the random states of a Markov process whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the current random states (see McKean–Vlasov processes, nonlinear filtering equation).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In other instances, a flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann–Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, and many others).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinear Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing in the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by the sampled empirical measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In contrast with traditional Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these mean-field particle techniques rely on sequential interacting samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The terminology *mean field* reflects the fact that each of the *samples* (a.k.a. particles, individuals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empirical measures of the process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] When the size of the system tends to infinity, these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical interaction between particles vanishes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Suppose one wants to know the expected value $\mu$ of a population (and knows that $\mu$ exists), but does not have a formula available to compute it.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The simple Monte Carlo method gives an estimate for $\mu$ by running n simulations and averaging the simulations' results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] It has no restrictions on the probability distribution of the inputs to the simulations, requiring only that the inputs are randomly generated and are independent of each other and that $\mu$ exists.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A sufficiently large n will produce a value for m that is arbitrarily close to $\mu$ ; more formally, it will be the case that, for any $\epsilon >0$ , $|\mu -m|\leq \epsilon$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Suppose we want to know how many times we should expect to throw three eight-sided dice for the total of the dice throws to be at least T .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The dice throws are randomly distributed and independent of each other.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] If n is large enough, m will be within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Choose the desired confidence level – the percent chance that, when the Monte Carlo algorithm completes, m is indeed within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Let z be the z -score corresponding to that confidence level.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Let $s^{2}$ be the estimated variance, sometimes called the "sample" variance; it is the variance of the results obtained from a relatively small number k of "sample" simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Note that, when the algorithm completes, $m_{k}$ is the mean of the k results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] If $n\leq k$ , then $m_{k}=m$ ; sufficient sample simulations were done to ensure that $m_{k}$ is within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] An alternative formula can be used in the special case where all simulation results are bounded above and below.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Choose a value for $\epsilon$ that is twice the maximum allowed difference between $\mu$ and m .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Let $0<\delta <100$ be the desired confidence level, expressed as a percentage.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Let every simulation result $r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{i},\ldots ,r_{n}$ be such that $a\leq r_{i}\leq b$ for finite a and b .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cost associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In general the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which may incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a single sample is high.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, the embarrassingly parallel nature of the algorithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) through parallel computing strategies in local processors, clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previously understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to estimate uncertainties in the simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations invert this approach, solving deterministic problems using probabilistic metaheuristics (see simulated annealing).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the Buffon's needle problem, in which π can be estimated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi first experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In the late 1940s, Stanisław Ulam invented the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was working on nuclear weapons projects at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclear weapon.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A colleague of von Neumann and Ulam, Nicholas Metropolis, suggested using the name *Monte Carlo*, which refers to the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to gamble.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods were central to the simulations required for further postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Von Neumann, Nicholas Metropolis and others programmed the ENIAC computer to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a fission weapon core, in the spring of 1948.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at Los Alamos for the development of the hydrogen bomb, and became popularized in the fields of physics, physical chemistry, and operations research.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Air Force were two of the major organizations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Carlo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in many different fields.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carlo methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of Henry P.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] McKean Jr. on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parabolic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] An earlier pioneering article by Theodore E.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Harris and Herman Kahn, published in 1951, used mean-field genetic-type Monte Carlo methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologies are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. metaheuristic) in evolutionary computing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The origins of these mean-field computational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of Alan Turing on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of Feynman–Kac path integrals.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The use of sequential Monte Carlo in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] It was in 1993, that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work the first application of a Monte Carlo resampling algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the system.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on a related "Monte Carlo filter", and the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989–1992 by P.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechanism.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines and Terry Lyons, and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral and Terry Lyons.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] There is no consensus on how *Monte Carlo* should be defined.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] For example, Ripley defines most probabilistic modeling as *stochastic simulation*, with *Monte Carlo* being reserved for Monte Carlo integration and Monte Carlo statistical tests.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Sawilowsky distinguishes between a simulation, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a technique that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical properties of some phenomena.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Kalos and Whitlock point out that such distinctions are not always easy to maintain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stochastic process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneously as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sampling." Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the Gelman-Rubin statistic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results of these experiments are not well known.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown parameters, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation methods do not always require truly random numbers to be useful (although, for some applications such as primality testing, unpredictability is vital).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, pseudorandom sequences, making it easy to test and re-run simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The only quality usually necessary to make good simulations is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a certain sense.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] What this means depends on the application, but typically they should pass a series of statistical tests.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Testing that the numbers are uniformly distributed or follow another desired distribution when a large enough number of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and most common ones.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Weak correlations between successive samples are also often desirable/necessary.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Pseudo-random number sampling algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a given probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Low-discrepancy sequences are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Methods based on their use are called quasi-Monte Carlo methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] No statistically significant difference was found between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and RDRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 107 random numbers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carlo simulations – for example, deterministic modeling using single-point estimates.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best guess" estimate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for each input variable are chosen and the results recorded.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a probability distribution for each variable to produce hundreds or thousands of possible outcomes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The results are analyzed to get probabilities of different outcomes occurring.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] This is because the "what if" analysis gives equal weight to all scenarios (see quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance), while the Monte Carlo method hardly samples in the very low probability regions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The samples in such regions are called "rare events".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs and systems with many coupled degrees of freedom.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In statistical physics, Monte Carlo molecular modeling is an alternative to computational molecular dynamics, and Monte Carlo methods are used to compute statistical field theories of simple particle and polymer systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo methods solve the many-body problem for quantum systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In radiation materials science, the binary collision approximation for simulating ion implantation is usually based on a Monte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In experimental particle physics, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing detectors, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In astrophysics, they are used in such diverse manners as to model both galaxy evolution and microwave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in the ensemble models that form the basis of modern weather forecasting.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for sensitivity analysis and quantitative probabilistic analysis in process design.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The need arises from the interactive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change relies on Monte Carlo methods in probability density function analysis of radiative forcing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of computational biology, for example for Bayesian inference in phylogeny, or for studying biological systems such as genomes, proteins, or membranes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or *ab initio* frameworks depending on the desired accuracy.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particular molecule to see if some chemical reaction is happening for instance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical experiment, thought experiments can be conducted, e.g. breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing the local/global structure, or introducing external fields.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Path tracing, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Repeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of the samples to converge on the correct solution of the rendering equation, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics rendering methods in existence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawilowsky.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] To provide implementations of hypothesis tests that are more efficient than exact tests such as permutation tests (which are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critical values for asymptotic distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in Bayesian inference.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] This sample then approximates and summarizes all the essential features of the posterior.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the negative log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of the Fisher information matrix.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomization and permutation tests.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] An approximate randomization test is based on a specified subset of all permutations (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations have been considered).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified number of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if a permutation is drawn twice—or more frequently—for the efficiency of not having to track which permutations have already been selected).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called Monte-Carlo tree search that is useful for searching for the best move in a game.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Possible moves are organized in a search tree and many random simulations are used to estimate the long-term potential of each move.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A black box simulator represents the opponent's moves.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Play a simulated game starting with that node.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ancestors.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the value of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully corresponding to whether or not that node represents a good move.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games such as Go, Tantrix, Battleship, Havannah, and Arimaa.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The US Coast Guard utilizes Monte Carlo methods within its computer modeling software SAROPS in order to calculate the probable locations of vessels during search and rescue operations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Each simulation can generate as many as ten thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Search patterns are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to optimize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detection (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Ultimately this serves as a practical application of probability distribution in order to provide the swiftest and most expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncertainty that would affect the outcome of different decision options.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods in finance are often used to evaluate investments in projects at a business unit or corporate level, or other financial valuations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] They can be used to model project schedules, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall project.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Additionally, they can be used to estimate the financial impact of medical interventions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in their applications for harassment and domestic abuse restraining orders.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] It was proposed to help women succeed in their petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially reducing the risk of rape and physical assault.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] However, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfectly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The study ran trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of the success level of the proposed program as a whole.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book publications based on book genre in Malaysia.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book's price according to book genre in the local market.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo results were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond of and was used to compare book publications between Malaysia and Japan.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Nassim Nicholas Taleb writes about Monte Carlo generators in his 2001 book *Fooled by Randomness* as a real instance of the reverse Turing test: a human can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart from a generated one.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve various problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also Random number generation) and observing that fraction of the numbers that obeys some property or properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The method is useful for obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analytically.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carlo integration.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Deterministic numerical integration algorithms work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when the functions have many variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] First, the number of function evaluations needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] For example, if 10 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then 10100 points are needed for 100 dimensions—far too many to be computed.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] This is called the curse of dimensionality.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Second, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an iterated integral.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] 100 dimensions is by no means unusual, since in many physical problems, a "dimension" is equivalent to a degree of freedom.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase in computation time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] As long as the function in question is reasonably well-behaved, it can be estimated by randomly selecting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of the function values at these points.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] By the central limit theorem, this method displays $\scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}$ convergence—i.e., quadrupling the number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dimensions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A refinement of this method, known as importance sampling in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more frequently where the integrand is large.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] To do this precisely one would have to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an integral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as stratified sampling, recursive stratified sampling, adaptive umbrella sampling or the VEGAS algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] A similar approach, the quasi-Monte Carlo method, uses low-discrepancy sequences.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important points more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the integral more quickly.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simulate random walks over it (Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Such methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, Gibbs sampling, Wang and Landau algorithm, and interacting type MCMC methodologies such as the sequential Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in numerical simulation is in numerical optimization.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The problem is to minimize (or maximize) functions of some vector that often has many dimensions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Many problems can be phrased in this way: for example, a computer chess program could be seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best evaluation function at the end.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In the traveling salesman problem the goal is to minimize distance traveled.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] There are also applications to engineering design, such as multidisciplinary design optimization.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models to solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configuration space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Reference is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and optimization.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The traveling salesman problem is what is called a conventional optimization problem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with the lowest total distance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] If instead of the goal being to minimize the total distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minimize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conventional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jams, time of day, etc.).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Probabilistic formulation of inverse problems leads to the definition of a probability distribution in the model space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] This probability distribution combines prior information with new information obtained by measuring some observable parameters (data).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is nonlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to describe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood model is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution power of the data is desired.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] In the general case many parameters are modeled, and an inspection of the marginal probability densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of models according to the posterior probability distribution and to analyze and display the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods of model properties is conveyed to the spectator.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] This can be accomplished by means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit formula for the *a priori* distribution is available.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm, can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possibly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex *a priori* information and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo-deep/monte-carlo-method] The method's general philosophy was discussed by Elishakoff and Grüne-Yanoff and Weirich.
